      "text": "The principle of binary coding of systemic information processing can be analytically traced back directly to the concept of information. Bateson (1983: 582) defines \"information\" as \"difference that makes a difference\". Accordingly, no information can be generated without assigning a message to one side of a distinction. If a message is assigned to both sides of a system-specific code through follow-up communications, then this documents that its content cannot restrict the possibilities for continuing communication in the system, i.e. that it makes no difference and in this respect does not inform, but – by activating the mutually exclusive assignment possibilities – drives the code of the system into a [[Paradox]] and thus generates [[Noise]] in the system."
